# Narrative_Bible

## 1. Applies when
Strong worldbuilding, faction conflict, complex history, sci-fi/fantasy/political
setting, or many narrative red lines.

## 2. This document owns
Objective world truth; history timeline; faction logic and motives; technology /
magic / religion / culture rules; propaganda framing; world premises; narrative red lines.

## 3. This document does NOT own
Concrete dialogue; level performance; mission steps; the player's subjective
discovery process (those belong to Narrative_Script).

## 4. Recommended chapter structure
1. Document role & usage · 2. World premises · 3. History timeline · 4. Factions ·
5. Tech / rules · 6. Propaganda · 7. Narrative red lines · 8. Continuity checklist · 9. TODO

## 5. Common boundaries
- Bible vs Script — objective truth vs how it is discovered/performed.
- Bible vs Naming — what it *is* in the world vs what it is *called*.

## 6. Common audit rules
- World truth must not be scattered into Narrative_Script.
- High-risk recurring facts are anchored (`FACT-…`) and referenced via `REF:`.
- Faction facts are single-owned here, not re-maintained in Character docs.
